By Oct '23, everything changed. War touched my homeland, I lost my job, and a project I'd dedicated years to was failing. Amidst this, I headed to a wedding in South Africa, a place far from friendly to my country. It sounded crazy, but it was the start of something new.

Leaving my digital life behind, I discovered resilience and insight in the least expected places. This journey taught me that sometimes, you find clarity and innovation not in holding on, but in letting go. More to come on how these lessons reshaped my approach to design and life

Facebook and Insta are down?

Starting as a simple break, this journey morphed into an essential mind reset. Suddenly, everything’s lighter, and ideas are bursting forth. This experience has shown me the incredible power and clarity that come from truly stepping back and giving yourself space. 🧠💡

continuing the story: (https://app.yup.io/post/5b0cdc94-c7e3-4b05-b56f-0048bae4181c)
🧘‍♂️ Landed in South Africa & embraced a full digital detox. No calls, no emails, just life. It was the reset I needed—sometimes, stepping back shows the way forward. 🌍✨

A moment of clarity hit me: Why keep delaying dreams? Chasing the northern lights with my dad became the first step. Spontaneous? Absolutely. Full of excitement? Beyond words. It's about transforming dreams into reality, one step at a time. 🌌

In the relentless hustle of design & startups, it’s too easy to miss the forest for the trees. This break shifted my perspective, offering invaluable new insights and igniting fresh ideas. It’s been a game-changer, reminding me to look at the larger canvas. 🖌️🔍

Has taking a step back ever led you to a major breakthrough? It’s fascinating how a little distance can change everything, offering new perspectives. I’m eager to hear your stories and how these moments reshaped your path. Let’s share and inspire each other! 👇

Every time I speak to a new designer that wants help with portfolios

It’s a fact: our products track every move, and we’ve stopped noticing its impact. We think this is just how things are. It works, so why change it? This mindset is known as habitual behavior. #productdesign

I love nuggets 🍗—not the ones you eat at McDonald’s, but the ones in the products I use every day. This year, I’m all about the @browsercompany great UX that Arc browser offers. It shows how small changes to everyday actions can make a huge difference. #UX #delight

As UX designers, it’s our job to break this habituality & present a better UX.
🕵️‍♀️ Question what seems obvious.
👀 Sometimes, the feature that works needs a change no one thought it needed.
😌 Look for small, easy changes—they can have a great effect at low cost.
#UXdesign
